# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dry-sump
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dry-sump/aeolipile] An **aeolipile**, **aeolipyle**, or **eolipile**, also known as a **Hero's** (or **Heron's**) **engine**, is a simple, bladeless radial steam turbine which spins when the central water container is heated.
[src:dry-sump/aeolipile] Torque is produced by steam jets exiting the turbine.
[src:dry-sump/aeolipile] The Greek-Egyptian mathematician and engineer Hero of Alexandria described the device in the 1st century CE, and many sources give him the credit for its invention.
[src:dry-sump/aeolipile] However, at least one source credits Vitruvius as the first to describe this appliance in his *De architectura* (c.
[src:dry-sump/aeolipile] The aeolipile is considered to be the first recorded steam engine or reaction steam turbine, but it is neither a practical source of power nor a direct predecessor of the type of steam engine invented during the Industrial Revolution.
[src:dry-sump/aeolipile] The name – derived from the Ancient Greek name Αἴολος and the Latin word *pila* – translates literally to 'the ball of Aeolus', Aeolus being the Greek god of the air and wind.
[src:dry-sump/aeolipile] Because it applies steam to perform work, an aeolipile (depicted in profile) is used as the symbol for the U.S.
[src:dry-sump/aeolipile] Navy's Boiler Technician Rate, as it was for the earlier Watertender, Boilermaker, and Boilerman ratings.
[src:dry-sump/aeolipile] The aeolipile usually consists of a spherical or cylindrical vessel with oppositely bent or curved nozzles projecting outwards.
[src:dry-sump/aeolipile] When the vessel is pressurised with steam, the gas is expelled out of the nozzles, which generates thrust due to the rocket principle as a consequence of the 2nd and 3rd of Newton's laws of motion.
[src:dry-sump/aeolipile] When the nozzles, pointing in different directions, produce forces along different lines of action perpendicular to the axis of the bearings, the thrusts combine to result in a rotational moment (mechanical couple), or torque, causing the vessel to spin about its axis.
[src:dry-sump/aeolipile] Aerodynamic drag and frictional forces in the bearings build up quickly with increasing rotational speed (rpm) and consume the accelerating torque, eventually cancelling it and achieving a steady state speed.
[src:dry-sump/aeolipile] Typically, and as Hero described the device, the water is heated in a simple boiler which forms part of a stand for the rotating vessel.
[src:dry-sump/aeolipile] Where this is the case, the boiler is connected to the rotating chamber by a pair of pipes that also serve as the pivots for the chamber.
[src:dry-sump/aeolipile] Alternatively the rotating chamber may itself serve as the boiler, and this arrangement greatly simplifies the pivot/bearing arrangements, as they then do not need to pass steam.
[src:dry-sump/aeolipile] This can be seen in the illustration of a classroom model shown here.
[src:dry-sump/aeolipile] Both Hero and Vitruvius draw on the much earlier work by Ctesibius (285–222 BCE), also known as Ktēsíbios or Tesibius, who was an inventor and mathematician in Alexandria, Ptolemaic Egypt.
[src:dry-sump/aeolipile] He wrote the first known treatises on the science of compressed air and its uses in pumps.
[src:dry-sump/aeolipile] It is not known whether the aeolipile was put to any practical use in ancient times, and if it was seen as a pragmatic device, a whimsical novelty, an object of reverence, or some other thing.
[src:dry-sump/aeolipile] A source described it as a mere curiosity for the ancient Greeks, or a "party trick".
[src:dry-sump/aeolipile] Hero's drawing shows a standalone device, and was presumably intended as a "temple wonder", like many of the other devices described in *Pneumatica*.
[src:dry-sump/aeolipile] Vitruvius, on the other hand, mentions use of the aeolipile for demonstrating the physical properties of the weather.
[src:dry-sump/aeolipile] This account was preserved by the royal Spanish archives at Simancas.
[src:dry-sump/aeolipile] It is proposed that de Garay used Hero's aeolipile and combined it with the technology used in Roman boats and late medieval galleys.
[src:dry-sump/aeolipile] Here, de Garay's invention introduced an innovation where the aeolipile had practical usage, which was to generate motion to the paddlewheels, demonstrating the feasibility of steam-driven boats.
[src:dry-sump/aeolipile] This claim was denied by Spanish authorities.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatic-aircraft] An **aerobatic aircraft** is an aerodyne (a heavier-than-air aircraft) used in aerobatics, both for flight exhibitions and aerobatic competitions.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatic-aircraft] Most fall into one of two categories, aircraft used for training and by flight demonstration teams, which are often standard trainers or fighters, and aircraft especially designed for aerobatics, usually at the expense of other attributes, such as stability, carrying passengers or endurance.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] Most aerobatic maneuvers involve rotation of the aircraft about its longitudinal (roll) axis or lateral (pitch) axis.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] Other maneuvers, such as a spin, displace the aircraft about its vertical (yaw) axis.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] Manoeuvres are often combined to form a complete aerobatic sequence for entertainment or competition.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] Aerobatic flying requires a broader set of piloting skills and exposes the aircraft to greater structural stress than for normal flight.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] In some countries, the pilot must wear a parachute when performing aerobatics.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] Aerobatic training enhances a pilot's ability to recover from unusual flight conditions, and thus is an element of many flight safety training programs for pilots.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] While many pilots fly aerobatics for recreation, some choose to fly in aerobatic competitions, a judged sport.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] In the early days of flying, some pilots used their aircraft as part of a flying circus to entertain.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] Maneuvers were flown for artistic reasons or to draw gasps from onlookers.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] In due course some of these maneuvers were found to allow aircraft to gain tactical advantage during aerial combat or dogfights between fighter aircraft.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] Aerobatic aircraft fall into two categories—specialist aerobatic, and aerobatic capable.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] Specialist designs such as the Pitts Special, the Extra 200 and 300, and the Sukhoi Su-26M and Sukhoi Su-29 aim for ultimate aerobatic performance.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] This comes at the expense of general purpose use such as touring, or ease of non aerobatic handling such as landing.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] At a more basic level, *aerobatic capable* aircraft, such as the Cessna 152 Aerobat or the R2160 Acrobin, can be dual purpose—equipped to carrying passengers and luggage, as well as being capable of basic aerobatic figures.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] Aerobatic maneuvers flown in a jet-powered aircraft are limited in scope as they cannot take advantage of the gyroscopic forces that a propeller driven aircraft can exploit.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] Jet-powered aircraft also tend to fly much faster, which increases the size of the figures and the length of time the pilot has to withstand increased g-forces.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] Jet aerobatic teams often fly in formations, which further restricts the maneuvers that can be safely flown.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] Aerobatics done at low levels and for an audience is called "stunt flying".
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] To enhance the show effect of aerobatic manoeuvres, smoke is sometimes generated; the smoke allows viewers to see the path travelled by the aircraft.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] Due to safety concerns, the smoke is not a result of combustion but is produced by the vaporization of fog oil into a fine aerosol, achieved either by injecting the oil into the hot engine exhaust or by the use of a dedicated device that can be fitted in any position on the aircraft.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] The first military aerobatic team to use smoke at will during displays was Fleet Air Arm 702 Squadron "The Black Cats" at the Farnborough Airshow in September 1957.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] Aerobatics are typically performed in aeroplanes and gliders, but are not limited solely to fixed-wing aircraft, as they can also be performed in specific helicopters, such as the MBB Bo 105, Westland Lynx and Eurocopter EC120 Colibri.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] The British Army, Royal Navy, Spanish Air Force and the Indian Air Force have helicopter display teams.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] Aerobatics are taught to military fighter pilots as a means of developing flying skills and for tactical use in combat.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] Many aerobatic manoeuvres were indeed developed in military conflicts, e.g. the Immelmann turn or Split S.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] Aerobatics demands extensive training and practice to avoid accidents.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] Accidents due to aerobatic manoeuvres are very rare in competition aerobatics; most of them happen when performing formation flying or stunt flying at very low levels at airshows or air racing.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] Low-level aerobatics are extremely demanding and airshow pilots must demonstrate their ability before being allowed to gradually reduce the height at which they may fly their show.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] In the European Union, aerobatics requires special training and a rating.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] In Canada, no licence is required to perform aerobatics, but to carry passengers during aerobatics a pilot must have at least 10 hours dual flight instruction of aerobatic manoeuvres, or 20 hours of total aerobatic experience.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] Aerobatic flying competitions are a worldwide phenomenon, rather like the Olympic games, and are governed by the FAI Aerobatics Commission (CIVA).
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] Competitions start at Primary, or Graduate level (in UK "Beginners") and proceed in complexity through Sportsman (in UK "Standard"), Intermediate and Advanced, with Unlimited being the top competition level.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] Experienced aerobatic pilots have been measured to pull ±5 g for short periods while unlimited pilots can perform more extreme maneuvers and experience higher g levels -possibly up to +8/−6 g.
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] The limits for positive g are higher than for negative g and this is due to the ability to limit blood pooling for positive g maneuvers, but it is generally accepted that +9 g for more than a few seconds will lead to loss of consciousness (also known as GLOC).
[src:dry-sump/aerobatics] Aerobatics are likely to be seen at public airshows in the form of stunt flying.
[src:dry-sump/air-cooling] In all cases, the air has to be cooler than the object or surface from which it is expected to remove heat.
[src:dry-sump/air-cooling] This is due to the second law of thermodynamics, which states that heat will only move spontaneously from a hot reservoir (the heat sink) to a cold reservoir (the air).
[src:dry-sump/air-cooling] When operating in an environment with lower air pressure like high altitude or airplane cabins, the cooling capacity has to be derated compared to that of sea level.
[src:dry-sump/air-cooling] A rule-of-thumb formula to note: 1 – (h/17500) = derating factor.
[src:dry-sump/air-cooling] Where *h* is the height over sea level in meters.
[src:dry-sump/air-cooling] And the result is the factor that should be multiplied with the cooling capacity in [W] to get the cooling capacity at the specified height over sea level.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] A particulate **air filter** is a device composed of fibrous or porous materials which removes particulates such as smoke, dust, pollen, mold, viruses, and bacteria from the air.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] Filters containing an adsorbent or catalyst such as charcoal (carbon) or baking sodamay also remove odors and gaseous pollutants, such as volatile organic compounds or ozone.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] Air filters are typically constructed of foam, pleated paper, cotton, or spun fiberglass.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] Oil bath air filters have fallen out of favour aside from niche uses.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] Air ionizers use a different method, static electric charge, than air filters to attract and remove dust particles but they may also be supplemented with an air filter.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] High efficiency particulate arrester (HEPA), originally called high-efficiency particulate absorber but also sometimes called high-efficiency particulate arresting or high-efficiency particulate arrestance, is a type of air filter.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] Filters meeting the HEPA standard have many applications, including use in clean rooms for IC fabrication, medical facilities, automobiles, aircraft and homes.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] The filter must satisfy certain standards of efficiency such as those set by the United States Department of Energy (DOE).
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] Varying standards define what qualifies as a HEPA filter.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] The two most common standards EN 1822 and ASME AG-1 require an air filter must remove (from the air that passes through) 99.95% (European Standard) or 99.97% (ASME standard) of particles that have a size greater than or equal to 0.3 μm.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] The cabin air filter, also known in the United Kingdom as a pollen filter, is typically a pleated filter that is placed in the outside-air intake for the vehicle's passenger compartment.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] Some of these filters are rectangular, while others are uniquely shaped to fit the available space of particular vehicles' outside-air intakes.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] The first automaker to include a disposable filter to keep the ventilation system clean was the Nash Motors "Weather Eye", introduced in 1940.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] A reusable heater core filter was available as an optional accessory on Studebaker models beginning in 1959, including Studebaker Lark automobiles (1959-1966), Studebaker Gran Turismo Hawk automobiles (1962-1964) and Studebaker Champ trucks (1960-1964).
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] The filter was an aluminum frame containing an aluminum mesh and was located directly above the heater core.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] The filter was removed and installed from the engine compartment through a slot in the firewall.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] A long, thin rubber seal plugged the slot when the filter was installed.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] The filter could be vacuumed and washed prior to installation.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] Clogged or dirty cabin air filters can reduce airflow available to the cabin vents, as well as introduce allergens into the cabin air stream.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] Since the cabin air temperature depends upon the flow rate of the air passing through the heater core, the evaporator, or both, clogged filters can greatly reduce the effectiveness and performance of the vehicle's air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] At the point of retail to the consumer, cabin air filter suppliers do not share performance testing characteristics listed below.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] However, some cabin air filter manufacturers do print a minimum efficiency reporting value (MERV) filter rating or cite N95 (however disclaim any NIOSH compliance) on their cabin air filter retail boxes.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] Pleat spacing (inversely pleat count) of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] Airflow and pressure drop of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] The combustion air filter prevents abrasive particulate matter from entering the engine's cylinders, causing mechanical wear, oil contamination, and change to emissions performance.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] Many modern fuel injected vehicles use a pleated paper filter element in the form of a flat panel, usually placed inside a plastic box connected to the throttle body with duct work.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] The overall unit (filter and housing, and duct work together) is called the **air cleaner**.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] Air intake filter media technology improvements have helped increase overall efficiency of gas turbine air-compressors by using simulation tools to optimize aerodynamics and fluid dynamics.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] Pleated paper filter elements are the nearly exclusive choice for automobile engine air cleaners, because they are efficient, easy to service, and cost-effective.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] The "paper" term is somewhat misleading, as the paper filter media is constructed differently from papers used for writing or packaging, by employing binding resins or surface modifications.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] The paper is pleated/bent in a zig-zag shape to increase the filtration surface area of the paper encountered by the airflow path, in the range of 50 times that of the air opening.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] There is a persistent belief among tuners, reinforced by advertising for aftermarket non-paper replacement filters manufacturers, that paper filters flow poorly enough to restrict engine performance.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] Oil-wetted polyurethane foam elements are used in some aftermarket replacement automobile air filters.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] Foam was in the past widely used in air cleaners on small engines on lawnmowers and other power equipment, but automotive-type paper filter elements have largely supplanted oil-wetted foam in these applications.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] Foam filters are still commonly used on air compressors for air tools up to 5 horsepower (3.7 kW).
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] Due to the way dust is captured on foam filters, large amounts may be trapped without measurable change in airflow restriction.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] Oiled cotton gauze is employed in a growing number of aftermarket automotive air filters marketed as high-performance items.[2] In the 1970's, with the introduction of the Fiat Abarth SS versions, cotton gauze air filters as OE automotive engine filters gained market traction.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] Metal Mesh (stainless steel for rust resistance) is another example of an air filter media which can be ordered with different mesh counts to adjust for desired performance characteristics.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] An oil bath air cleaner consists of a sump containing a pool of oil and an insert which is filled with fiber, mesh, foam, or another coarse filter media.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] The cleaner removes particles by adhering them to the oil-soaked filter media; as opposed to traditional filtration, the openings in the filter media are much larger than the particles that are to be filtered.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] When the cleaner is assembled, the media-containing body of the insert sits a short distance above the surface of the oil pool.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] The rim of the insert overlaps the rim of the sump.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] This U-turn takes the air at high velocity across the surface of the oil pool.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] Heavier (and typically larger) dust and dirt particles in the air cannot make the turn due to their inertia, so they fall into the oil and settle to the bottom of the base bowl.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] Lighter (and typically smaller) particles stick to the filtration media in the insert, which is wetted by oil droplets aspirated there by normal airflow.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] The constant aspiration of oil onto the filter media slowly carries most of the finer trapped particles downward and the oil drips back into the reservoir where the particles accumulate.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] Oil bath air cleaners were very widely used in automotive and small engine applications until the widespread industry adoption of the paper filter in the early 1960s.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] Such cleaners are still used in off-road equipment where very high levels of dust are encountered, for oil bath air cleaners can sequester a great deal of dirt relative to their overall size without loss of filtration efficiency or airflow.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] In the early 20th century (about 1900 to 1930), water bath air cleaners were used in some applications (cars, trucks, tractors, and portable and stationary engines).
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] They worked on roughly the same principles as oil bath air cleaners.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] For example, the original Fordson tractor had a water bath air cleaner.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] By the 1940s, oil bath designs had displaced water bath designs because of better filtering performance.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] Bulk solids handling involves the transport of solids (mechanical transport, pneumatic transport) which may be in a powder form.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] Many industries are handling bulk solids (mining industries, chemical industries, food industries) which requires the treatment of air streams escaping the process so that fine particles are not emitted, for regulatory reasons or economical reasons (loss of materials).
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] As a consequence, air filters are positioned at many places in the process, especially at the reception of pneumatic conveying lines where the quantity of air is important and the load in fine particle quite important.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] Filters can also be placed at any point of air exchange in the process to avoid that pollutants enter the process, which is particularly true in pharmaceuticals and food industries.
[src:dry-sump/air-filter] European standard EN 779, on which the above table is based, remained in effect from 2012 to mid-2018, when it was replaced by ISO 16890.
[src:dry-sump/airbox] An **airbox** is an empty chamber on the inlet of most combustion engines.
[src:dry-sump/airbox] It collects air from outside and feeds it to the intake hoses of each cylinder.
[src:dry-sump/airbox] Older engines drew air directly from the surroundings into each individual carburetor.
[src:dry-sump/airbox] Modern engines instead draw air into an airbox, which is connected by individual hoses to each carburetor or directly to the intake ports in fuel-injected engines, thus avoiding an extra intake manifold.
[src:dry-sump/airbox] The airbox allows the use of one air filter instead of multiples, reducing complexity.
[src:dry-sump/airbox] Developments arising from concerns about engine emissions during the late 1970s allow the airbox to collect pump gases from the crankcase and the tank air vent and re-feed them to the engine.
[src:dry-sump/airbox] Since the 1990s, engine designers also sought to exploit the properties of oscillating gas to improve performance.
[src:dry-sump/airbox] Many high-performance motorcycles have the airbox fed from funnels in the front of the bike, where increased pressure forces more air into the intake and thus improves power.
[src:dry-sump/airbox] Examples of this ram-air intake construction are the SRAD models of the Suzuki GSX-R750, the Kawasaki Ninja ZX-6R or the BMW S1000RR.
[src:dry-sump/airbox] Secondly, designers exploit a property of air cavities known as Helmholtz resonance.
[src:dry-sump/airbox] Flow through the airbox is optimal at its resonance frequency, which depends on airbox volume and the inlet area and length of the snorkel.
[src:dry-sump/airbox] The resonance is typically chosen to be at a medium speed where torque otherwise drops, caused by valve timing overlap.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] An **aircraft engine**, often referred to as an **aero engine**, is the power component of an aircraft propulsion system.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] Aircraft using power components are referred to as **powered flight**.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] Most aircraft engines are either piston engines or gas turbines, although a few have been rocket powered and in recent years many small UAVs have used electric motors.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] The market for aircraft engines, especially jet engines, has very high barriers to entry.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] Aircraft engines use highly advanced technology and materials, take around eight years and billions of dollars or euros to develop, and must pass exacting safety certifications by aviation safety authorities.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] Consequently, entering the engine market is extremely capital- and time-intensive, which helps protect existing manufacturers from competition.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] The last successful entry in the global market for jet engines was General Electric in the 1970s.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] These barriers to entry make the market very lucrative for existing manufacturers.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] As of 2025, the leading jet engine manufacturers reported shareholder returns from between 100 and 1,000 percent over the last five years, compared to small or negative returns for their principal clients, Airbus and Boeing.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] The engines themselves are typically sold at a loss, but manufacturers derive their profits from the sale of maintenance services and spare parts over the roughly thirty-year lifespan of an engine, following the razor and blades business model.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] This creates a perverse incentive for manufacturers to slow the production or delay the delivery of new engines, because they profit most from the use of old engines, which need more service and spare parts than new ones.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] This contributed to the unavailability of new engines, creating a bottleneck for Airbus and Boeing's efforts to increase aircraft production in the post-COVID resurgence of aviation after 2023.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] A radial engine has the cylinders placed in a circle around the crankshaft.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] The engine is air-cooled, which can be a problem since they may overheat.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] Compared to liquid-cooled engines, radial engines have the advantage of being more rugged and capable of absorbing damage.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] Rotating radial engines have the cylinders in a circle around the crankcase, as in a radial engine, (see above), but the crankshaft is fixed to the airframe and the propeller is fixed to the engine case, so that the crankcase and cylinders rotate.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] The advantage of this arrangement is that a satisfactory flow of cooling air is maintained even at low airspeeds, retaining the weight advantage and simplicity of a conventional air-cooled engine without one of their major drawbacks.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] The first practical rotary engine was the Gnome Omega designed by the Seguin brothers and first flown in 1909.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] Its relative reliability and good power to weight ratio changed aviation dramatically.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] The Wankel engine is about one half the weight and size of a traditional four-stroke cycle piston engine of equal power output, and much lower in complexity.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] In an aircraft application, the power-to-weight ratio is very important, making the Wankel engine a good choice.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] Because the engine is typically constructed with an aluminium housing and a steel rotor, and aluminium expands more than steel when heated, a Wankel engine does not seize when overheated, unlike a piston engine.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] This is an important safety factor for aeronautical use.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] Considerable development of these designs started after World War II, but at the time the aircraft industry favored the use of turbine engines.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] It was believed that turbojet or turboprop engines could power all aircraft, from the largest to smallest designs.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] The Wankel engine did not find many applications in aircraft, but was used by Mazda in a popular line of sports cars.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] The French company Citroën had developed Wankel powered RE-2 helicopter in 1970's.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] In modern times the Wankel engine has been used in motor gliders where the compactness, light weight, and smoothness are crucially important.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] Starting in the 1930s, attempts were made to produce a practical aircraft diesel engine.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] In general, Diesel engines are more reliable and much better suited to running for long periods of time at medium power settings.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] Improvements in Diesel technology in automobiles (leading to much better power-weight ratios), the Diesel's much better fuel efficiency, and the high relative taxation of AVGAS compared to Jet A1 in Europe have all seen a revival of interest in the use of diesels for aircraft.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] Thielert Aircraft Engines converted Mercedes Diesel automotive engines, certified them for aircraft use, and became an OEM provider to Diamond Aviation for their light twin.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] Financial problems have plagued Thielert, so Diamond's affiliate — Austro Engine — developed the new AE300 turbodiesel, also based on a Mercedes engine.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] A turboprop consists of an intake, reduction gearbox, compressor, combustor, turbine, and a propelling nozzle.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] Air enters the intake and is compressed by the compressor.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] Jet fuel is then added to the compressed air in the combustor, where it then combusts.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] The hot combustion gases expand through the turbine stages, generating power at the point of exhaust.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] Some of the power generated by the turbine is used to drive the compressor and electric generator.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] The gases are then exhausted from the turbine, but do not provide enough power to create a major portion of the total thrust, since almost all of the engine's power is used to drive the propeller.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] A **turboshaft** engine is a form of gas turbine that is optimized to produce shaft horsepower rather than jet thrust.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] The engine has two major parts assemblies: the 'gas generator' and the 'power section'.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] The gas generator consists of the compressor, combustion chambers with ignitors and fuel nozzles, and one or more stages of turbine.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] The power section consists of additional stages of turbines, a gear reduction system, and the shaft output.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] The gas generator creates the hot expanding gases to drive the power section; the engine accessories may be driven either by the gas generator or by the power section.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] A number of electrically powered aircraft, such as the QinetiQ Zephyr, have been designed since the 1960s.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] In France in late 2007, a conventional light aircraft powered by an 18 kW electric motor using lithium polymer batteries was flown, covering more than 50 kilometers (31 mi), the first electric airplane to receive a certificate of airworthiness.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] On 18 May 2020, the Pipistrel E-811 was the first electric aircraft engine to be awarded a type certificate by EASA for use in general aviation.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] The E-811 powers the Pipistrel Velis Electro.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] Many big companies, such as Siemens, are developing high-performance electric engines for aircraft use; also, SAE shows new developments in elements as pure Copper core electric motors with a better efficiency.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] A hybrid system as emergency back-up and for added power in take-off is offered for sale by Axter Aerospace, Madrid, Spain.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] The term *advanced technology engine* refers to the modern generation of jet engines.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] A rocket turbine engine is a combination of two types of propulsion engines: a liquid-propellant rocket and a turbine jet engine.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] Its power-to-weight ratio is a little higher than a regular jet engine, and it works at higher altitudes.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] At the April 2018 ILA Berlin Air Show, Munich-based research institute de:Bauhaus Luftfahrt presented a high-efficiency composite cycle engine for 2050, combining a geared turbofan with a piston engine core.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] The 11,200 lb (49.7 kN) engine could power a 50-seat regional jet.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] Its cruise TSFC would be 11.5 g/kN/s (0.406 lb/lbf/hr) for an overall engine efficiency of 48.2%, for a burner temperature of 1,700 K (1,430 °C), an overall pressure ratio of 38 and a peak pressure of 30 MPa (300 bar).
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] Although engine weight increases by 30%, aircraft fuel consumption is reduced by 15%.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] Sponsored by the European Commission under Framework 7 project LEMCOTEC, Bauhaus Luftfahrt, MTU Aero Engines and GKN Aerospace presented the concept in 2015, raising the overall engine pressure ratio to over 100 for a 15.2% fuel burn reduction compared to 2025 engines.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] On multi-engine aircraft, engine positions are numbered from left to right from the point of view of the pilot looking forward, so for example on a four-engine aircraft such as the Boeing 747, engine No.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] 1 is on the left side, farthest from the fuselage, while engine No.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] 3 is on the right side nearest to the fuselage.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] In the case of the twin-engine English Electric Lightning, which has two fuselage-mounted jet engines one above the other, engine No.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] 1 is below and to the front of engine No.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] Refineries blend Avgas with tetraethyllead (TEL) to achieve these high octane ratings, a practice that governments no longer permit for gasoline intended for road vehicles.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] The shrinking supply of TEL and the possibility of environmental legislation banning its use have made a search for replacement fuels for general aviation aircraft a priority for pilots’ organizations.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] Model aircraft typically use nitro engines (also known as "glow engines" due to the use of a glow plug) powered by glow fuel, a mixture of methanol, nitromethane, and lubricant.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] Electrically powered model airplanes and helicopters are also commercially available.
[src:dry-sump/aircraft-engine] Small multicopter UAVs are almost always powered by electricity, but larger gasoline-powered designs are under development.
[src:dry-sump/dry-sump] A **dry sump** system is a method to manage the lubricating motor oil in four-stroke and large two-stroke reciprocating internal combustion engines.
[src:dry-sump/dry-sump] The dry sump system uses two or more oil pumps and a separate oil reservoir, as opposed to a conventional wet sump system, which uses only the main sump (U.S.: oil pan) below the engine and a single pump.
[src:dry-sump/dry-sump] A dry sump engine requires a pressure relief valve to regulate negative pressure inside the engine so that internal seals are not inverted.
[src:dry-sump/dry-sump] Dry sump lubrication is common on larger diesel engines such as those used in ships, as well as gasoline engines used in racing cars, aerobatic aircraft, high-performance personal watercraft, and motorcycles.
[src:dry-sump/dry-sump] Dry sumps may be chosen for these applications due to increased reliability, oil capacity, reduction of oil starvation under high g-loads, or other technical or performance reasons.
[src:dry-sump/dry-sump] Dry sumps may be unsuitable for some applications, usually due to their increased cost, complexity, or bulk.
[src:dry-sump/dry-sump] Engines are both lubricated and cooled by oil that circulates throughout the engine, feeding various bearings and other moving parts and then draining, via gravity, into the sump at the base of the engine.
[src:dry-sump/dry-sump] In the wet-sump system of nearly all production automobile engines, oil that is not actively circulating is in the sump.
[src:dry-sump/dry-sump] A pump collects oil from the sump and directly circulates it back through the engine.
[src:dry-sump/dry-sump] In a dry-sump system, oil still collects at the base of the engine, but into a much smaller sump, where one or more scavenge pumps draw it away and transfer it to a (usually external) reservoir, where it is both cooled and de-aerated before being recirculated through the engine by a pressure pump.
[src:dry-sump/dry-sump] The reservoir is usually tall, narrow, and designed with the oil outlet at the very bottom and baffles above the outlet, for uninhibited oil supply even during sloshing.
[src:dry-sump/dry-sump] Dry sump pump operation consists of a pressure stage and a scavenging stage.
[src:dry-sump/dry-sump] Although the term "stages" is commonly used to describe the work of the multiple pumps, they typically run in parallel rather than in series as might be implied by the term.
[src:dry-sump/dry-sump] The pressure stage draws oil from the bottom of the reservoir and passes it through the filter and into the engine itself.
[src:dry-sump/dry-sump] An adjustable pressure regulator ensures that oil pressure is kept stable at different engine speeds.
[src:dry-sump/dry-sump] The dry-sump system requires at least two pumps – one pressure and one scavenge – and sometimes as many as four or five scavenge pumps are used to minimize the amount of oil in the sump.
[src:dry-sump/dry-sump] The pressure pump and scavenge pumps are frequently mounted on a common crankshaft, so that a single pulley at the front of the system can run as many oil pumps as the engine design requires.
[src:dry-sump/dry-sump] It is common practice to have one scavenge pump per crankcase section; however, in the case of inverted engines (typically aircraft engines), it is necessary to employ separate scavenge pumps for each cylinder bank.
[src:dry-sump/dry-sump] Therefore, an inverted V engine would have a minimum of two scavenge pumps and one pressure pump.
[src:dry-sump/dry-sump] Dry sump systems may optionally be designed to keep the engine's crankcase at lower than atmospheric pressure (i.e. a partial vacuum) by sealing the crankcase and allowing the scavenge pumps to draw out both oil and gases.
[src:dry-sump/dry-sump] Pressure equilibrium in such an engine will be reached when the rate of gases entering the crankcase (blow-by gases past the piston rings, but also air leaks and oil vapor) equals the rate of gas removal from the scavenge pump capacity beyond what is required to remove just the oil.
[src:dry-sump/dry-sump] Alternatively, the crankcase may be kept near atmospheric pressure by venting it to the oil reservoir, which in turn is vented into the engine's air intake or to outside air.
[src:dry-sump/dry-sump] A dry-sump system offers many advantages over a wet-sump.
[src:dry-sump/dry-sump] Dry sumps are common on larger diesel engines such as those used for ship propulsion, largely due to increased reliability and serviceability.
[src:dry-sump/dry-sump] They are also commonly used in racing cars and aerobatic aircraft due to problems with g-forces, reliable oil supply, power output, and vehicle handling.
[src:dry-sump/dry-sump] The C6, C7, and C8 generations of the Chevrolet Corvette Z06 use dry sump lubrication, which necessitates an initial oil change after 500 miles (800 km).
[src:dry-sump/dry-sump] Dry sump lubrication is particularly useful for motorcycles, which tend to be operated more vigorously than other road vehicles.
[src:dry-sump/dry-sump] However, narrower engines can be mounted lower and should ideally use dry-sump lubrication.
